'''August Alphonse Derbès''' (8 May 1818, Marseille – 27 January 1894, Marseille) was a [[French people|French]] professor of [[Natural history|naturalist]], [[zoology|zoologist]] and [[botany|botanist]] at the [[Aix-Marseille University|University of Marseille]] who studied reproduction of [[sea urchin]]s and of [[algae]].<ref>{{cite web|title=August Alphonse Derbès at IPNI|url=http://ipni.org/ipni/idAuthorSearch.do?id=2136-1&back_page=%2Fipni%2FeditAdvAuthorSearch.do%3Ffind_abbreviation%3D%26find_surname%3DDerbes%26find_isoCountry%3D%26find_forename%3D%26output_format%3Dnormal|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Derbès was the first scientist to observe the fertilization of an egg in an animal when he detailed the process of an envelope forming around the [[gamete]] during sea urchin reproduction, a process now known to be associated with [[Calcium in biology|Ca<sup>2+</sup>]] release.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Briggs|first=Elissa|author2=Gary M. Wessel|title=In the beginning… Animal fertilization and sea urchin development|journal=Developmental Biology|year=2006|volume=300|pages=15–26|doi=10.1016/j.ydbio.2006.07.014}}<!--|accessdate=28 July 2012--></ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Parrington|first=John|author2=Davis, Lianne C.|author3= Galione, Antony|author4= Wessel, Gary|title=Flipping the switch: How a sperm activates the egg at fertilization|journal=Developmental Dynamics|date=1 August 2007|volume=236|issue=8|pages=2027–2038|doi=10.1002/dvdy.21255|pmid=17654712}}<!--|accessdate=28 July 2012--></ref>

