'''Creeper''' was an experimental computer program written by Bob Thomas at [[BBN Technologies|BBN]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lyle.smu.edu/~tchen/papers/statmethods2004.pdf|title=The Evolution of Viruses and Worms|author=Thomas Chen, Jean-Marc Robert|date=2004|accessdate=2016-03-02}}</ref> Its original iteration was designed to move between [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]] [[PDP-10]] [[mainframe computer]]s running the [[TOPS-20|TENEX operating system]] using the [[ARPANET]], with a later version by [[Ray Tomlinson]] designed to copy itself between computers rather than simply move.<ref name="core war">{{cite web|url=http://corewar.co.uk/creeper.htm|title=Core War: Creeper & Reaper|author=John Metcalf|date=2014|accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> This self-replicating version of Creeper is generally accepted to be the first [[computer worm]].<ref name="IEEE"/><ref name="Guardian"/> 

The program was not actively [[Malware|malicious software]] as it caused no damage to data, the only effect being a message it output to the teletype reading "I'm the creeper: catch me if you can".<ref name="Guardian">[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/oct/23/internet-history From the first email to the first YouTube video: a definitive internet history]. Tom Meltzer and Sarah Phillips. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 23 October 2009</ref> 

==Reaper==
{{Infobox software| name                   = sawya
| title                  = Reaper
| released               = 1972
| discontinued           = 19733333333
| operating system       = [[TOPS-20|TENEX]]
| author                 = [[Ray Tomlinson]]
}}
'''Reaper''' was a similar program created by [[Ray Tomlinson]] to move across the ARPANET and delete the self-replicating Creeper.<ref name="core war">{{cite web|url=http://corewar.co.uk/creeper.htm|title=Core War: Creeper & Reaper|author=John Metcalf|date=2014|accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref>

==Cultural impacts==
The conflict between Creeper and Reaper served as inspiration for the [[programming game]] ''[[Core War]]'',<ref name="core war" /> while fictionalized versions of Reaper have been used as antagonists in the [[anime]] ''[[Digimon Tamers]]'' and the [[visual novel]] ''[[Digital: A Love Story]]''.

