{{otheruses|seeding (disambiguation)}}


[[File:Flow around sphere, being visualized by seeding flow with smoke.jpg|300px|thumb|Flow around a sphere being visualized by seeding the flow with smoke.]]
[[File:Hairpinvortex.jpg|400px|thumb|Visualization of hairpin vortex structure, made visible by seeding the flow with colored dye.]]

'''Seeding''' a material is a concept used in [[fluid dynamics]] to describe the act of introducing specific [[particulate]]s or other foreign substances into a stream of [[fluid]] being evaluated. An altered fluid will be described as having a '''seeded''' flow.<ref name=Handbook/>

==Details==
{{expand-section|date=September 2015}}
These particulates are generally small enough to be carried by the fluid but large enough to be picked up using a [[flow visualization]] technique, such as [[particle image velocimetry]] (PIV).  In reference to [[aerodynamic]] testing, such as [[wind tunnel]] testing, water tunnel testing, or any other test investigating the flow of a fluid which may be invisible to the naked eye, seeding a flow is often the only way to take visual measurements.  Simple examples of a seeded flow include the introduction of smoke into a low speed wind tunnel to see the general path of the air, or injecting colored dye into a water tunnel to see secondary flow structures such as hairpin vortices.{{fact|date=September 2015}}

As stated in ''The Handbook of Fluid Dynamics'', an ideal seeding particle should have uniform properties such that its density is the same as the fluid that it's added to.<ref name=Handbook>{{citebook|title=The Handbook of Fluid Dynamics|first=Richard W.|last=Johnson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JBTlucgGdegC&pg=SA35-PA9&dq=%22seeding+the+flow%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBWoVChMIn8vGn8PwxwIVzBSSCh0uEA_A#v=onepage&q=%22seeding%20the%20flow%22&f=false|publisher=[[Springer Science & Business Media]]|date=1998|ISBN=9783540646129}}</ref>

