{{short description|popular science book by mathematician Ian Stewart}} {{Infobox book | name = The Mathematics of Life | image = Mathematics of Life cover.jpg | image_size = | caption = First edition cover | alt = Book cover, ''The Mathematics of Life'' | author = [[Ian Stewart (mathematician)|Ian Stewart]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | subject = [[Biology]], [[biomathematics]] | genre = Non-fiction | language = English | country = United States | published = 2011 | publisher = [[Basic Books]] | media_type = Print, e-book | pages = 368 pp. | awards = | isbn = 978-0465022380 | oclc = 670481599 | dewey = | congress = }}
'''''The Mathematics of Life''''' is a 2011 popular science book by mathematician [[Ian Stewart (mathematician)|Ian Stewart]], on the increasing role of [[mathematics]] in [[biology]].<ref name="googlebooks">{{cite book | title = The Mathematics of Life (Google eBook) | publisher = Google | url = https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Mathematics_of_Life.html?id=u4X4cRaZlJUC | accessdate = September 16, 2014 | isbn = 9780465024407 | date = 2011-06-07 }}</ref>
==Overview== Stewart discusses the mathematics behind such topics as [[population growth]], [[speciation]], [[brain]] function, [[chaos theory]], [[game theory]], [[biological network|network]]ing, [[symmetry in biology|symmetry]], and [[animal coloration]], with little recourse to equations.<ref name="kirkus">{{cite news | title = The Mathematics of Life by Ian Stewart | newspaper = [[Kirkus Reviews]] | date = April 5, 2011 | url = https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/ian-stewart/mathematics-life/ | accessdate = September 16, 2014 }}</ref> He identifies six revolutions which modernized biology:<ref name="nyjb">{{cite news | last = Parker | first = Nicole | title = The Mathematics of Life | newspaper = New York Journal of Books | url = http://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/mathematics-life | accessdate = September 16, 2014 }}</ref>
#The [[Timeline of microscope technology|invention of the microscope]] #A [[Taxonomy (biology)|systematic means of classifying species]] #Evidence of [[evolution]] #The expansion of the field of [[genetics]] #The [[History of molecular biology|discovery of the structure of DNA]] #The [[Mathematical and theoretical biology|application of new mathematics]] to biology
==Reception== Writer [[Alex Bellos]] described ''The Mathematics of Life'' as "a testament to the versatility of maths and how it is shaping our understanding of the world."<ref name=Bellos>{{cite news|last1=Bellos|first1=Alex|author-link=Alex Bellos|title=Mathematics of Life by Ian Stewart - Review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/apr/16/mathematics-of-life-ian-stewart-review|accessdate=4 May 2015|work=The Guardian|date=April 15, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called the book "an ingenious overview of biology with emphasis on mathematical ideas—stimulating but requiring careful reading despite the lack of equations."<ref name="kirkus"/> A review in ''[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]]'' noted that the book "does an admirable job of unfolding the mathematics undergirding so much of the research being carried out today in the many fields that comprise the subject of biology."<ref name=adam>{{cite journal|last1=Adam|first1=John|title=Putting the "X" in Biology: A Review of The Mathematics of Life|journal=Notices of the American Mathematical Society|date=December 2011|volume=58|issue=11|pages=1572–1578|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/201111/rtx111101572p.pdf|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>
Mathematician and science writer [[Keith Devlin]] criticized the book, writing that "readers of the author's many general-audience books on mathematics may be surprised to find themselves at times frustrated by his latest outing, which is marred by overlapping and often repetitious passages."<ref name=devlin>{{cite news|last1=Devlin|first1=Keith|authorlink1=Keith Devlin|title=New Angles on Biology: Life sciences, meet mathematics: How viruses resemble Buckminster Fuller's geodesic dome, and other discoveries|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304066504576345382084988252|accessdate=4 May 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 9, 2011}}</ref>
